When you think of brunch, the usual suspects probably come to mind: fluffy pancakes, buttery croissants, maybe a mimosa (or two). But breadsticks? Not so much. These humble, crunchy rods of dough are usually relegated to the side of a pasta dish or handed out in a breadbasket at Italian restaurants. But here's a delicious truth: breadsticks are brunch’s most underrated MVP—and it’s time we start treating them as more than just a sidekick.
Whether you're hosting a laid-back Sunday get-together or looking to jazz up your weekend breakfast routine, here are some fun, flavorful, and totally unexpected ways to bring breadsticks to the brunch table.
1. Breadstick Breakfast Skewers
Who says skewers are just for the grill? Take warm breadsticks, cut them into bite-sized pieces, and alternate them on wooden skewers with cherry tomatoes, cubes of cheese, olives, and thinly sliced prosciutto or turkey bacon. It's like a deconstructed breakfast sandwich, but way more fun to eat. Drizzle with a balsamic glaze or serve with a side of herbed yogurt dip.
Bonus: They look Instagram-worthy without much effort.
2. French Toast Breadsticks
Yes, you read that right. Dip breadsticks into a classic French toast batter (eggs, milk, cinnamon, a dash of vanilla), then fry them up in a skillet until golden. Serve with maple syrup, powdered sugar, and fresh berries. They’re like mini handheld French toasts with a satisfying crunch.
Tip: Use softer breadsticks for this so they soak up the batter without falling apart.
3. Savory Breadstick Dippers with Eggy Goodness
Pair crispy breadsticks with soft-boiled or poached eggs for a simple but elevated touch. Serve them upright in a jar or small glass next to a runny egg in an egg cup. Dip and enjoy—it’s elegant, it’s simple, and it’ll have people talking.
Want to take it up a notch? Wrap your breadsticks in pancetta or thin bacon before baking them in the oven for a smoky, salty twist.
4. Build-Your-Own Brunch Board
Charcuterie boards are basically a brunch essential now. Why not build a brunch board that’s centered around breadsticks? Think of them as your edible utensils. Arrange them around small bowls of whipped feta, avocado smash, smoked salmon mousse, hummus, and flavored butters.
Add hard-boiled eggs, fruit, mini quiches, and roasted veggies for color and variety. Breadsticks give your guests the perfect way to scoop, dip, and savor without needing a knife or fork.
5. Breadstick Bloody Mary Stirrers
Want to make your Bloody Mary extra memorable? Swap the boring celery stick for a spicy breadstick coated in chili flakes, garlic powder, or even sesame seeds. It not only looks cool but also adds crunch and flavor. Bonus points if you top the glass with a mini skewer of pickles, olives, and cheese cubes.
6. Mini Breadstick Sandwiches
Split soft breadsticks in half and turn them into little sandwiches. Fill with scrambled eggs, avocado, crispy bacon, and a touch of aioli. Or go Mediterranean with sun-dried tomatoes, arugula, and goat cheese. They’re perfect finger food and ideal for guests who want something hearty without committing to a full sandwich.
Final Crumbs
Breadsticks may not have a glamorous reputation, but with a little creativity, they can be the surprise star of your next brunch. Whether you're dunking them in eggs, dressing them up with cheese and charcuterie, or sweetening them into French toast, these versatile little sticks deserve a spot at the table.
So next time you're planning a brunch, think beyond bagels and croissants. Give breadsticks a chance to shine—you might just start a new trend.

